<HEADLINE>
FT  29 AUG 92 / French doubts on Maastricht grow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OPPOSITION to the Maastricht treaty on European union is continuing to grow
in France despite the government's campaign efforts.
The latest opinion poll shows that 53 per cent of those polled plan to vote
against ratifying the treaty in next month's referendum.
The poll, compiled by CSA for Le Parisien newspaper, is the third this week
indicating a majority may vote No in the September 20 referendum.
Two previous polls showed majorities of 51 per cent and 52 per cent against
Maastricht. Three other polls published this week suggested small majorities
in favour of the treaty.
Support for Maastricht has been falling since President Francois Mitterrand
announced the referendum in June, fuelling fears throughout the EC that the
French will reject it. This depressed Europe's stock markets throughout the
week.
The leaders of one of the two main right-wing opposition parties, Mr Jacques
Chirac of the RPR, has since joined his rival, Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing
of the UDF, in the pro-Maastricht lobby. He was previously reluctant to do
so because of concern about splits in his own party on Europe.
The RPR, which has a 75 per cent majority against Maastricht, yesterday
announced it would be dividing its allocation of broadcast airtime between
the Yes and No factions when the official pre-referendum campaign starts on
September 7.
The only consolation for the pro-Maastricht campaigners from yesterday's
poll was that a high proportion of the CSA sample - 40 per cent - had still
not decided which way to vote in the referendum, or whether to vote at all.
Bourse on its toes, page 19
</TEXT>
