FT  28 AUG 92 / Science GCSE results welcomed: British Association for the
Advancement of Science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE British Association gave an enthusiastic welcome to this week's results
of the GCSEs, the main examination for 16-year-olds in England and Wales.
The association said it was particularly pleased about the rapid increase in
entries to the broadly based science exams, which had risen from 145,000 in
1991 to 240,000 this year.
Professor Jeff Thompson, association chairman, said the switch from
individual science subjects - biology, chemistry and physics - to 'broad and
balanced' science was good news because 'it will provide a better
understanding of science as part of a general education for the majority of
students'.
He denied suggestions that the new GCSE science courses represented any
lowering of standards.
According to an association statement the science results reflected 'the
increasing familiarity of teachers with the demands of the new examination
and the hard work which has been going on over the last five years'.
Sir David Attenborough, association president, forecast that the upturn in
GCSE science results might lead to an improvement in science A-level results
in two or three years' time. Peat bogs are being destroyed by drainage and
harvesting, the meeting was told.
Conservationists said the bogs enable scientists to trace environmental and
archaeological changes over thousands of years because the acidic and
oxygen-free conditions preserve organic materials.
The meeting heard that harvesting particularly affected lowland raised bogs
 -those which grow above the mineral water table.
</TEXT>
