<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / New policies on energy urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW policies to remove distortions in the energy market could cut emissions
of carbon dioxide in the UK by 40 per cent as well as putting money back
into the economy, according to a study published today by Friends of the
Earth, the environmental pressure group.
The report, by Dr Tim Jackson, an independent consultant on energy and
environment policy, says failure to take action will mean market distortions
will continue to misdirect Pounds 2bn a year on investment in uneconomic and
carbon-intensive technologies.
Friends of the Earth proposes measures including the linking of mortgage tax
relief to energy efficiency in the home; tighter energy efficiency standards
for buildings and appliances; new price regulations for electricity and gas
companies to encourage energy saving; a carbon tax of between 4 per cent and
7 per cent to provide money for grants, loans and subsidies of up to Pounds
400m a year to spend on energy efficiency; and a National Energy Bank to
distribute these grants.
The study says a series of regulatory and fiscal distortions as well as a
lack of information in the market for energy services means householders and
businesses do not see improving energy efficiency to be in their own
economic interests, in spite of its value to the economy.
Efficiency Without Tears. Friends of the Earth, 26-28 Underwood St, London
N1 7JQ. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
