FT  28 AUG 92 / Acorn aims new range at parents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACORN, the Cambridge-based personal computer manufacturer which dominates
the UK schools market, is attempting to break out of its educational niche
with a swathe of products aimed at the home and professionals.
Acorn says its computers are used by 90 per cent of schoolchildren. It now
hopes to persuade parents that they should use the same make of computer as
their children use at school. A television advertising campaign will suggest
the systems are equally well suited for work and play.
Acorn, in which Olivetti of Italy has a majority stake, has had some
difficult years because of the recession and changes in schools' purchasing
policies. It hopes customers will be attracted by the power of its ARM
microprocessor, a version of which is to be used by Apple Computers of the
US in a revolutionary pocket computer called Newton.
Acorn's product list includes a home computer for Pounds 499, a 'home
office' system for Pounds 999 plus VAT, and a Pounds 250 electronic notebook
which is the first product of Acorn's collaboration with Psion, the UK
portable computer manufacturer.
The notebook is essentially Psion's Series 3 pocket computer with software
modified to suit it to the computing needs of secondary-school children.
Last year Acorn recovered from a poor first half to record pre-tax profits
of Pounds 274,000, against Pounds 1.58m the year before. The company's
position in the school market seems secure but the consumer and professional
personal market is experiencing weak demand and intense price cutting.
