<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (14): Supplier to the multinationals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE early 1960s, Mr Low Kim Teow ran a small business in Penang making
grills for windows and doors.
Mr Low's shophouse was like many hundreds that can still be seen in the
streets of Penang: a bustling workshop in front, with a table for meals in
the midst of all the grease and the tools. In the back there was a storeroom
and kitchen, and upstairs was the living area. But Mr Low and his family
have long since left the shophouse behind them.
He and his two sons now run an engineering company, supplying machines and
fixtures to the multinational electronics plants of Penang.
In the 1970s Mr Low saw that the newly arrived multinationals needed a
variety of local components and services - and set about supplying them. Now
the Lowcompany provides Intel and other companies with a range of
fabrication equipment, much of it highly sophisticated.
The company - like most Chinese businesses very much a family-run,
privately-held concern - employs more than 100 and had a turnover of
MDollars 13m last year.
In some cases a multinational will ask Low Kim Teow to make a particuar
piece of equipment. More often the Low company will use its own design and
engineering workshops to come up with machines that streamline the
production processes in the big plants.
This includes a machine for loading computer chips for Intel, and recently
the company has moved into the business of making moulds for computer
housings and other electronics goods.
'We now want to diversify as much as possible,' says Mr Low Kee Lin, one of
the sons, who is company managing director. 'We want to make a big push with
exports. Despite the labour shortages, we still feel we can produce
mouldings, fabrication equiment and other items more cheaply and efficiently
here. We are already making some sales abroad.'
Back in the 1960s, when Mr Low was still making iron door grills,
unemployment in Penang was nearly 20 per cent, and people were leaving the
island in search of jobs. But that was before the electronics companies
arrived in Penang. Low Kim Teow Engineering recently had to go to India - to
recruit engineers for its plant.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-5708</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIBBCAE9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920828
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (13): Silicone ousts spice on betel-nut
island / State profile of Penang
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE'S A Nirvana Street in Penang. The name may be a little bit of an
overstatement but Penang does have a few heavenly qualities.
There's the old funicular railway, built by a wayward Swiss engineer earlier
this century, that takes you up to the lush, cool heights of Penang hill.
There's the esplanade with its food stalls to suit even the most indulgent
of stomachs, the old town shophouses, the Indian shrines and Chinese
temples.
Penang, 'the betel nut island', was a vital British trading port in the 18th
and 19th centuries, a collection point for the pepper, rattan, camphor and
opium that was traded back and forth between India and China. But now there
is more silicone than spice in Penang. The island - and Province Wellesley
across the new bridge on the mainland - has grown to be the main centre for
Malaysia's electronics industry, the country's biggest export earnings
sector.
At the last count, 120 factories in Penang, employing nearly 75,000 people,
were either directly involved or in some way connected with the electronics
and electrical goods industries.
Almost all of the world's main electronics companies are there. Intel, with
6,000 workers, has its biggest off-shore plant in Penang. National
Semiconductor expects to export more than MDollars 1bn of products from its
Penang plant this year. The Penang Development Corporation (PDC), set up in
the late 1960s to promote inward investment, estimates that Penang now
accounts for about 50 per cent of Malaysia's total MDollars 35bn electronics
and electrical equipment exports.
From the first, Penang was a pioneer. The PDC set up the first free trade
zone in Malaysia in 1972 and, soon after, the electronics firms began
arriving, attracted by plentiful supplies of land and labour, with English
language skills readily available. Textile companies also invested heavily,
though their importance in the local economy has declined by comparison with
the electronics sector. Foreign companies could retain 100 per cent equity
holdings if they fulfilled certain conditions, including exporting most of
their product. They could also have full repatriation of profits.
Over the years, Penang has moved into more sophisticated areas of production
 -from purely assembly to actual component manufacturing. It now competes
with Singapore in many areas. The infrastructure has been improved, and
companies give the efficiency of Penang port as one of the major investment
attractions.
Linkages have developed with local businesses: a multitude of home grown
companies, some big, some merely a front shop room, now act as suppliers to
the electronics industry.
'Once we have the linkages in place, we feel more secure about these
companies' long-term commitment to Penang,' says Ms Lim Pao Li, of the PDC.
'A large proportion of components is now made locally, but we always have to
be aware of the changes in the industry and the problems we face.'
The number one problem in Penang, as in many other parts of Malaysia, is a
shortage of labour. Almost every factory gate has a vacancies sign. Many
hundreds of workers have to be bussed in and out of Penang each day from
areas several kilometres away. Foreign workers, mainly from Indonesia, have
started to be recruited. Factories complain of an increased incidence of
'job hopping'.
Penang realises that, in some of the more labour intensive areas, it will
not be able to compete with countries that have sufficient labour -
particularly Indonesia, Thailand and most recently, Vietnam. A semi-skilled
worker in a Penang factory might earn USDollars 10 per day. In Indonesia the
equivalent would be USDollars 1.50 per day.
A big increase in land prices is also causing many factories problems. And
the delicate racial question is never far away from any aspect of Malaysian
life. Penang is looked upon as a mainly Chinese island; but Malays say that,
though they make up nearly 40 per cent of the population, they have very
little economic power. Increasingly, there are calls from the Malay
community for a more even distribution of the growing wealth of the betel
nut, now silicone, island.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
