<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (11): Privatisations this year
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Privatisations this year have included 30 per cent of Perusahaan Otomobil
Nasional, the maker of Malaysia's Mitsubishi-based Proton cars. This month,
the latest model, the Proton Saga Iswara, was launched in Kuala Lumpur by
the prime minister, Dr Mahathir Mohamad, seen (below) inspecting the new
Proton emblem. When he first announced the Proton project in the early
1980s, many critics predicted disaster. Yet today, every other car on the
Malaysian roads is a Proton, and the car is exported to 12 countries. As car
sales in most countries fall, capacity at the Proton factory is being
expanded, with plans to produce 150,000 cars a year by 1995.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-5710</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIBBCAE7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920828
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (9): A fillip for the capital markets -
Privatisation / The first decade of the government's programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHERE OTHERS have talked, Malaysia has acted. For the last decade, the
government has embraced privatisation with an enthusiasm rarely matched
elsewhere.
This year alone has seen the sale on the Kuala Lumpur stock market of 23 per
cent of the equity of Tenaga Nasional, the state electricity utility, and 30
per cent of Perusahaan Otomobil Nasional, the maker of Malaysia's
Mitsubishi-based Proton cars.
A total of 54 organisations have been privatised or partially privatised in
the last 10 years, according to official figures. Most of them were existing
government units sold to the private sector, and the rest new projects such
as roads which would once have been the sole responsibility of the
authorities.
It all began in 1983. Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the prime minister, initially had
differences with Mrs Margaret Thatcher, the British premier, but her
privatisation drive apparently caught his imagination.
By regional standards, government involvement in the Malaysian economy was
then exceptionally widespread, partly because of official efforts to speed
the transfer of assets to the Malay community from the wealthier Chinese.
Even in 1990, Malaysia's public expenditure amounted to 34.5 per cent of
gross national product, compared with 21.5 per cent in Singapore and 15 per
cent in Thailand.
'Hence we have to reorientate and downsize the public sector and promote
privatisation,' Mr Mohamad Sheriff Kassim, secretary-general at the finance
ministry, told a privatisation conference in Kuala Lumpur in June this year.
Government officials cite several advantages of the privatisation programme,
including windfall income of MDollars 6.7bn so far from the sale of
government shares in privatised corporations, reduced government spending
(privatisation has reduced the public sector workforce by about 65,000), and
increased efficiency.
They say the privatisation of the Klang Container Terminal in 1986 rapidly
reduced the average length of time each container stayed on the dock, while
the telephone network partially privatised in 1990 improved its service to
customers, and the concession granted to a private television channel (TV3)
in 1983 increased competition and benefited the viewing public.
Furthermore, the privatisation programme has helped to develop local capital
markets. Privatised companies account for a third of the capitalisation of
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange. Recently, says Mr Mohamed Sidek, senior
general manager of Arab-Malaysian Merchant Bank, 'we thought privatisation
may crowd out some other private sector initiatives, but it didn't' The
economic boom made sure of that.
So far, the government has focused on 'flagship' corporations, including
Malaysia Airlines System in 1985, in an attempt to ensure the success of the
privatisation programme. But the smaller state entities, some of them
unprofitable subsidiaries of state development corporations, need more
restructuring and are more difficult to dispose of.
On the government's own admission, 1991 was a disappointing year. Only five
out of the original 23 targeted projects were privatised, because of lengthy
and inconclusive negotiations between the government and private companies
on projects initiated by the private sector, the need for new laws to allow
for the privatisation of certain operations such as abattoirs and a failure
to agree on the valuation of assets to be sold.
However, a further 10 projects not included in the government's original
action plan were also sold, including provincial companies such as Kedah
Cement and Sabah Shipyard, bringing the 1991 total to 15.
Plans are also under consideration to privatise the railways, while the
government has shortlisted four proposals by private companies to build and
operate electricity generating plants.
Critics of the privatisation programme complain that the government has
either maintained a majority stake or control in many of the larger,
partially-privatised corporations, or effectively transferred control to
ruling political organisations such as the United Malays National
Organisation (Umno) or to influential individuals.
For example, United Engineers, a company linked to Umno, was awarded the
contract to complete the important north-south highway, a project which
recently announced large financing overruns, and will now cost a total of
MDollars 6bn. And a row erupted in parliament this year over allegations
that Mr S Samy Vellu, the minister of energy, posts and telecommunications
and leader of one of the parties in the National Front government, had
misappropriated 9m shares from the privatisation of Telekom Malaysia. The
dispute has yet to be resolved.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-5711</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIBBCAE6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920828
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (10): Helpful neighbours can also be a
liability - Tourism is the only service industry to run a surplus, but there
is anxiety at the central bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TO THE Malaysian tourism industry, Thailand is a source of both inspiration
and despair: inspiration, because of its longstanding success in attracting
foreign visitors; despair, because the political violence in Bangkok in May
has prompted some holidaymakers to cancel their visits to south-east Asia.
Malaysia is anxious to emulate Thailand's successful handling of the tourist
trade, not least because the Kuala Lumpur government is concerned about the
services deficit in the balance of payments, and tourism is the only service
industry to run a surplus.
By 1990 - or Visit Malaysia Year 1990, if you are in the tourism business -
tourists had become the country's third largest source of foreign exchange,
after manufacturing and crude oil, although arrivals have since fallen from
that year's total of 7.5m visitors.
In its latest annual report, the Malaysian central bank notes with some
Angst that the country's tourism industry is lagging behind those of its
neighbours in Asean (the Association of South East Asian Nations) in terms
of the sector's share of gross national product.
Furthermore, half of Malaysia's visitors are short-stay tourists from
Singapore (day-trippers are not counted); the average length of stay in
Malaysia is put at 4.6 nights, against 6.1 for Thailand. Average per diem
spending is MDollars 345 in Thailand, compared with only MDollars 128 in
Malaysia; Thailand has more than three times as many hotel rooms.
With holidays in the developed world becoming longer and longer, tourists
increasingly favour multi-destination holidays. Malaysia has used the
opportunity to expand its business, particularly by forging links with
Thailand and Singapore, the two main air travel gateways to south-east Asia
(the slogan for the Malaysia-Singapore tie-up is: 'Fascinating Malaysia,
surprising Singapore: two great countries, one great holiday').
The potential disadvantages of such links were graphically illustrated in
May, when troops killed at least 50 pro-democracy demonstrators on the
streets of Bangkok. Many holidays through the Bangkok gateway were
cancelled, at least in the short term, and, in the words of Mr Ahmad Bakri
Shabdin, the director general of the Malaysia Tourism Promotion Board, 'when
they cancel, they cancel both legs of a journey'.
That setback, and the competing lure of the recent Olympic Games in
Barcelona, have left Malaysia struggling to reach its target of 6.6m
visitors for 1992, although the start of the new high season is yet to come.
The Gulf war helped push down 1991 arrivals to 5.9m from 1990's 7.5m, and
Malaysia had been hoping for a brisk revival.
'Come 1992, we were hoping for a recovery, but we are now being affected
very much by the global recession,' says Mr Bakri Shabdin. 'It has been
compounded by the fact that in 1991 many countries developed domestic
tourism.'
In the European market, Malaysia finds itself competing with more convenient
destinations in America or the Mediterranean; and even in Asia, the most
important source of tourism, there are problems with the decline of the
Japanese incentive travel market.
Malaysia has much to offer the tourist, from tropical beach holidays, scuba
diving and hill resorts in the peninsula to jungle treks and mountain walks
in Borneo, but it has never been able to project a clear image to its
potential customers. The jury is still out on the success of Visit Asean
Year 1992 - an attempt to link the six Asean members (Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand) - but it appears that
Asean is too little known outside the region to make much impact on the
average tourist.
Tourism officials point vaguely at Malaysia's ethnic diversity and
interesting history, but admit that the name Malaysia conjures up different
and hazy images for different people if it conjures up anything at all.
'Since 1990 we've decided to highlight our natural resources,' says Mr Bakri
Shabdin. 'That's one thing we have that is uniquely Malaysian. We are
acknowledged as being the home of the oldest rainforest in the world.'
Leaving aside the controversy over whether that rainforest is being
irreparably destroyed by logging, Malaysia also realised from its 1990
campaign that it was worth making an effort to promote the country
vigorously as a tourist destination, and worth linking its promotions to
special events already scheduled for Malaysia.
'We learned from 1990 that there is a very marked correlation between events
and people arriving in the country,' says Mr Bakri Shabdin. 'We realise that
tourism is very much a consumer-oriented activity, and therefore we have to
continually make our presence felt in the global tourism market.'
The result was a decision to launch another Visit Malaysia Year in 1994  -
an idea first mooted as early as 1991 and formally inaugurated this year -
and to repeat the process every four years. This will fit conveniently with
the Commonwealth Games in Malaysia in 1998.
Malaysia has already started to release promotional material for the 1994
campaign, featuring a jungle scene with flowers, butterflies and a
waterfall. Tourists are curious, but it is questionable whether many foreign
visitors will be drawn to Malaysia by some of the advertised events -
including a squid-fishing festival, an Asean literature meeting, the Ipoh
half-marathon, the birthday of the state governor of Malacca and a
bird-singing competition - rather than by Malaysia's more permanent charms
of sun, sea, sand and jungle.
Perhaps the important ingredients for reviving the Malaysian tourism
industry will not only be the kite shows and Malaysian fruit festivals, but
also the continued investment in real estate (up to 70 hotels and resorts
are planned before the end of the decade and the number of hotel rooms is
increasing by 10 to 12 per cent a year), the proposed new airport, and a
recovery in the world economy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-5712</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIBBCAE5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920828
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (8): Economic health curbs worker
militancy - Manufacturing / Victor Mallet finds concern about the shortage
of much-needed skilled technicians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A dozen executives from manufacturing companies in Malaysia what worries
them the most, and the chances are that you will get a dozen identical
answers: the labour shortage.
Malaysia's economy has grown so quickly and its drive to industrialise has
been so successful that employers have been forced to increase wages faster
than the rate of inflation. They have even resorted to paying bonuses to
workers who recruit a friend for the factory.
'Today electronics workers sometimes change jobs because the other factory
has an air-conditioned canteen,' says the chief executive of one
multinational company.
Inflation is running at about 4.5 per cent, but most manufacturing wages
have been rising by between 8 and 15 per cent a year. Unemployment has
dropped to around 4.2 per cent - a level regarded by some employers as
effectively zero when it comes to suitable factory workers - and the labour
market in some areas is being further tightened as the numerous new foreign
investments, approved in 1990 and 1991, come on stream. Some companies spend
tens of thousands of ringgit (Malaysian dollars) a month bussing in workers
from ever larger catchment areas.
The labour shortage has been dramatised by the government's drive to
register illegal foreign workers - and by a deputy minister's mistaken claim
that a third of the foreigners who underwent medical checks for their work
permits were infected with sexually-transmitted diseases, including the
acquired immune deficiency syndrome (Aids).
About 320,000 guest workers, mostly Indonesians, were registered before the
deadline at the end of June, but thousands more are thought to remain in the
country unrecorded. Only 0.24 per cent of those tested were found to have
the virus which leads to Aids.
From the point of view of employers in the electronics sector, one of the
positive effects of the enforced higher wage regime has been to take the
heat out of a campaign by the Malaysian Trades Union Congress to establish a
national electronics union.
National unions in other industries are permitted, but the government of Dr
Mahathir Mohamad - with the full support of Japanese, American and other
employers - has forbidden the formation of a union in the important
electronics sector since 1972 and restricted workers to Japanese-style
in-house employee associations.
Despite the bitter taste left by a lingering dispute between trade unionists
and Harris Semiconductor of the US, the economic boom has dampened worker
militancy and allowed the growth of a rival trade union group - the
Malaysian Labour Organisation - which is regarded with approval by the
government, and which accepts in-house unions. Official figures show that
electronics workers earn the highest wages in manufacturing, an average of
MDollars 721 a month in 1991, compared with MDollars 526 for clothing
workers.
In the longer term, employers and senior government officials are concerned
about the shortage of the skilled technicians who will be needed to manage
Malaysia's proposed shift towards higher-technology industries.
Thailand and Indonesia are facing similar challenges.
'We are aware of this problem,' says Mr Low Peng Lum, director of industrial
promotion at the Malaysian Industrial Development Authority, 'and that is
why the government is putting a lot of emphasis now on human resource
development.'
Employers blame a shortage of Malay technicians on the government's policy
of funding university education in Bahasa (the local language) for
Bumiputras (Malays) - which they say produced too many social science and
arts graduates - while many Chinese were forced to pay for their own
education abroad and returned with technical qualifications and a useful
knowledge of English. 'The government policy on Bumiputeras has done the
opposite of what the government wanted,' says one foreign executive.
Most of the other problems identified by manufacturing companies -
occasional power shortages, telephone and data line problems, congested
ports and roads - are the result of Malaysia's rapid economic growth and the
consequent strains on communications, transport and other infrastructure.
Malaysia, which hosts such giants as Matsushita and Motorola, is now one of
the top three semiconductor exporters in the world, the largest
air-conditioner exporter and one of the biggest manufacturers of television
sets and video cassette recorders.
Since 1989, the manufacturing component of gross domestic product has been
rising by 14 per cent or more a year, and manufacturing's share of total GDP
had doubled to more than 28 per cent last year from 14 per cent in 1970.
The Malaysian electronics industry has matured quickly, moving from
'screwdriver' assembly operations to an emphasis on 'backward integration' -
domestic production of components. 'Now we see more people coming in to
build more components and parts,' says Mr Low.
In general, the aim is to concentrate on high-technology industry and add as
much value to the product in Malaysia as possible, while leaving behind
labour-intensive industries such as textiles.
'Malaysia wants to get into high technology,' says Mr Roger Bertelson,
managing director at Motorola Malaysia. 'They want to attract electronics
downstream manufacturers that can use a high proportion of the
semi-conductors made in the country.'
An executive from another multinational company says: 'These are not
screwdriver operations. Today all companies divert their screwdriver
operations to Indonesia, and people are considering going to Vietnam or
southern China.'
Malaysia has been so successful in developing its economy that it faces the
loss of tariff privileges on some of its exports - the US has already
withdrawn preferences for Malaysian rubber threads, Mr Low says  - and so
good at attracting foreign investors that it has been forced to become more
choosy.
Bank Negara, the central bank, expressed concern in its 1991 annual report
about what it called the country's 'narrow manufacturing base'. Although new
products made in Malaysia included toys, sporting goods, photographic
equipment and jewellery, it noted that electronics, textiles and
rubber-based products still accounted for 32 per cent of manufacturing
output and nearly 70 per cent of manufactured export earnings, making the
country vulnerable to the vagaries of the world economy.
Malaysia is attempting to reshape its industrial base by adjusting and
reducing foreign investment incentives, and encouraging more domestic
investment. 'We are now becoming selective,' says Mr Low. 'Incentives will
only be given to those industries which are high-tech, capital intensive. .
. We are beginning to feel some problems now with the supply of labour.'
Henceforth, for example, 100 per cent foreign ownership is allowed only if
the project exports 80 per cent of production or meets other criteria of
size or value added. The previous export level required was only 50 per
cent.
As a result of this and other changes, there was a surge of foreign
investment in 1990 and 1991 to gain the older and more advantageous
incentives. Foreign investment approvals rose from MDollars 8.7bn in 1989 to
MDollars 17.6bn in 1990, and dipped slightly to MDollars 16bn last year.
This year's half-year total of MDollars 9bn has been inflated by the
inclusion of a few exceptionally large petrochemical projects.
Critics of the Malaysian government complain that officials are slow to
begin a public debate when an economic problem emerges - whether it be a
labour shortage or a lack of electricity - but they acknowledge that the
authorities do respond to private lobbying and do eventually take action.
Few countries could have predicted or easily absorbed the economic growth
that Malaysia has seen in the last few years. 'Growth in Malaysia,' says one
businessman, 'has been beyond their best-case scenario.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page V
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-5713</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIBBCAE4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920828
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (5): Splits appear in Umno as its
opponents coalesce - Politics, Dr Mahathir presides over a delicate
structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON ONE level, politics in Malaysia is all about one man. After more than 10
years in power, Dr Mahathir Mohamad dominates the scene. A generally passive
media quotes his every word, the first items on the nightly television news
more often than not being devoted to Dr Mahathir's activities.
But Dr Mahathir presides over a delicate and at times shaky political
structure. There are divisions within his United Malays National
Organisation (Umno). Partners in the prime minister's National Front
government, though electorally weak, have to be constantly mollified and
appeased. The opposition shows signs of greater unity and, perhaps the most
precarious element of all in present day Malaysian politics, the government
is embroiled in increasingly bitter federal-state arguments with the
opposition-governed states of Kelantan and Sabah.
Umno has dominated Malaysian politics since the days of independence from
Britain. But there have been frequent splits within the organisation, and in
1987 Dr Mahathir was forced to form the present Umno Baru party, or New
Umno, after an attempted party putsch against his leadership and a court
ruling against the legality of the old party structure.
Umno represents the Malays, who make up more than than half of Malaysia's
18.5m population. Umno MPs are very dependent on continued support in their
home states, and have to echo views which at times run contrary to
government policy.
Some states, particularly the more conservative northern ones, want a
greater Umno commitment to moves towards a more Islamic society. There is
concern within some sections of Umno about the new direction in government
economic policy, with less emphasis now being given to the spread of wealth
as a natural right among the Bumiputra, or Malay, community.
At times, Umno bickering intrudes into international affairs: a recent
quarrel with Singapore about ownership of an island off the southern state
of Johor was seen by some as an attempt by dissident Umno elements in Johor
to embarrass Dr Mahathir, rather than a Kuala Lumpur-Singapore clash.
In the last elections, in late 1990, the National Front's share of the vote
dropped from 57 to 52 per cent, but it still has 127 of the 180 seats in the
lower house of parliament. Umno politicians hold the important cabinet
positions. The Malaysian Chinese Association, one of the main National Front
partners, is still tainted with past corruption charges, and has failed to
capture the hearts and minds of the majority of Malaysia's 30 per cent
Chinese community.
The Malaysian Indian Congress (MIC), another coalition partner, seems to
lurch from one scandal to another. Mr S Samy Vellu, the MIC leader and
minister of energy, telecommunications and posts in Dr Mahathir's
government, was last month asked by the country's anti corruption agency to
provide details of his financial assets, following investigations into the
misappropriation of 9m shares in Telekom Malaysia, the country's second
biggest listed company. In recent weeks MPs have listened to a number of
allegations by the opposition that another leading MIC member and former
parliamentary deputy speaker has been involved in various group sex
exploits.
The opposition has attacked government for what it regards as its
unwillingness to tackle corruption and its increasingly high handed
approach. Mr Lim Kit Siang, leader of the opposition Democratic Action Party
(DAP) says there is an increasingly 'anti-democratic trend' in Malaysia.
Mr Razaleigh Hamzah, once a close colleague of Dr Mahathir but now heading a
rival political party to Umno, has launched a broadside against the
government's industrialisation policy, saying that it will only lessen the
role of the Malays in the economic life of the country - a claim dismissed
as 'rubbish' by the government.
Some of the opposition groups have recently formed a coalition: while an
increased show of unity might make attacks on the government more effective,
the opposition is hampered by the apparent unwillingness of the media to
give detailed coverage to anti-government views. The opposition is also up
against the enormous financial resources of Umno, mostly derived from the
party's involvement in a myriad of business conglomerates and enterprises.
The federal-state battle is of greater concern to Dr Mahathir's government.
In the 1990 elections, the state of Kelantan, on the east coast of peninsula
Malaysia, voted out Umno and in Parti Islam Malaysia (PAS). Kelantan is the
most Islamic of the Malaysian states, with more than 90 per cent of the
population Moslem. Umno sees itself as the representative of Malay - by
extension Moslem - values and traditions. PAS, which emphasises the need for
more thorough Islamisation, is seen as a leading threat to Umno.
Dr Mahathir makes no secret of his anger that the people of Kelantan have
chosen PAS instead of Umno. Investors are shying away from Kelantan because
it is controlled by an opposition party, says the government. It says that
attempts by the Kelantan government to implement 'Hukum Hudud', the
traditional Islamic penal code which can mean the stoning of adulterers and
the amputation of the hands of thieves, will only mean that Kelantan will
become less developed. The Kelantan authorities accuse the federal
government of withholding development funds in order to punish the state for
voting against Umno.
In the state of Sabah, in East Malaysia, the situation is more complex. The
principal political party in the state, the Parti Bersatu Sabah (PBS), is
multi-racial, mainly representing Sabah's diverse native peoples. PBS was
formerly part of the National Front government, and Umno did not involve
itself in Sabah's politics. But this changed in the elections of 1990, when
the PBS decided to leave the coalition and support the rival Umno group, led
by Mr Razaleigh. Following this, Umno moved into Sabah and launched a
membership drive among the native peoples, who in official parlance are also
referred to as Bumiputras, though most are not Malays.
The PBS, which still controls Sabah's administration, accuses Umno of
importing its own racially-based politics into the state and threatening
stability. The government has brought corruption charges against Mr Joseph
Pairin Kitingan, head of the PBS and Sabah's chief minister. Mr Pairin's
brother has been detained under Malaysia's Internal Security Act, suspected
of plotting to have Sabah opt out of the Malaysian Federation.
Echoing the accusations of Kelantan, Sabah says Kuala Lumpur is punishing it
for not obeying Umno edicts and is hindering its development.
These political issues are manifesting themselves at a time of considerable
change in Malaysian society. As the country rapidly industrialises, it is
becoming less rural. Malays in particular are migrating in increasing
numbers to the cities. The government's New Economic Policy, in place over
the past 20 years, did succeed in transferring a proportion of the national
wealth into Malay hands. But Malays themselves see the divisions that have
arisen within their own group - between a monied, mainly urban elite and an
underprivileged rural class. Umno is nervous that the latter group could
desert the party and turn instead to PAS.
Over the years, Dr Mahathir has shown himself to be a highly skilled, and at
times ruthless, politician. In his mid-sixties, the prime minister sets a
fast pace and shows no signs of wishing to retire. At the moment, Mr Anwar
Ibrahim, the minister of finance, is viewed as the heir apparant.
'For the next five years,' said Dr Mahathir after the 1990 election, 'I will
be free from this kind of nasty politicking. I can concentrate on developing
the country, giving people a better life, improving their lot.'
His government has certainly improved the Malaysian economy. While growth
continues, the opposition and dissident elements within Umno will have
little opportunity to mount a clear challenge to Dr Mahathir's leadership.
But a change in economic circumstances could mean trouble. Few, least of all
Dr Mahathir, forget that the last challenge to the prime minister's
leadership was in 1987, a time when the clouds of recession were still
blowing across Malaysia.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
