</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Survey of Malaysia (7): New techniques needed - Agriculture
/ Kieran Cooke considers its diminishing role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Our traditional kampungs (villages) are actually more often full of
dilapidated pondok (shacks), dirty and without modern amenities. To lead a
life against the background of swaying palms and the full moon might be
beautiful as depicted in a painting, but to continue to do so might not be
suited to modern times' - Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the Malysian prime minister.
THE AGRICULTURAL sector was once the main engine of growth in the Malaysian
economy. But as the economy has grown, agriculture's role has diminished. As
the manufacturing sector has prospered, agriculture has had to battle
through increasingly difficult times, bringing considerable change to rural
life.
Malaysian agriculture is dominated by the country's wealth of primary
commodities, including rubber, palm oil and cocoa. In 1980, primary
commodities accounted for 43.7 per cent of total exports; but by 1991 they
made up barely 19 per cent. On the other hand, manufactured goods exports
made up 22.4 per cent of exports in 1980, but had risen to 65 per cent of
the total by 1991.
Due largely to the runaway growth of Malaysia's manufacturing sector,
agriculture's contribution to overall GDP has been declining: in 1991 it was
17.2 per cent, compared with 18.6 per cent in the previous year.
Such a trend is natural in an industrialising economy. But the speed at
which the change has taken place has caused problems. Furthermore the
manufacturing sector's growth is not entirely responsible for agriculture's
decline. The sector as a whole faces its own difficulties, with stagnant
growth and problems of scale and structure.
Over the past 20 years, the main thrust of government agricultural policy
has been support for smallholders and the sponsoring of state farms. The old
foreign-owned plantation companies, through government ownership
restrictions or due to their own financial constraints, found it
increasingly difficult to run profitable enterprises. The government poured
money into smallholder support schemes. Cheap credit facilities and a range
of other aids were readily available.
More than half the agricultural workers are Malays. Agricultural policy
dovetailed with overall government aims: to eradicate poverty and to give
the Bumiputras - mostly Malays - a greater share of national wealth. During
the past 20 years, poverty has been significantly reduced, while
smallholders and state farms now account for most commodity production. More
than 70 per cent of rubber production in 1991 came from smallholder units.
Policy is now changing. The government admits that the heavily subsidised
smallholder and state farm systems have been inefficient and excessively
bureaucratic. It now emphasises economies of scale and the need to move
towards more sophisticated production techniques, plus improved marketing.
Farmers' incomes have not kept pace with those in the manufacturing sector.
Smallholders have been reluctant to invest in new technology to improve
yields: while rubber yields per hectare in the estate sector increased last
year, they once again declined among smallholders. The government now
proposes a return to estate-type structures, with equity-holding
smallholders consolidated into private corporate entities. Foreign
investment in such areas is being encouraged.
The need to improve production techniques is crucial, in order to combat
domestic labour shortages and increased foreign competition. Malaysia as a
whole faces a labour shortage, but in agriculture the problem is critical.
Malays and to a lesser extent Indians - the traditional rubber 'tappers' -
have migrated to the cities, finding better-paying and less arduous jobs.
According to Bank Negara, the central bank, the total labour force in the
rubber industry was more than 11 per cent lower at the end of 1991 than at
the end of 1990.
Meanwhile, thousands of Indonesians and Bangladeshis, many without permits,
work in the plantation sector. A recent government clampdown on 'illegals'
has caused concern. The Malaysian Agricultural Producers Association says
output in the plantation sector could drop by as much as 30 per cent if all
'illegals' were deported.
Both Indonesia and Thailand, with low cost labour, are now bigger rubber
producers than Malaysia.
Malaysia still retains its commanding position as world's leading palm oil
producer, but competition for markets is becoming greater each year. In the
worldwide rubber industry, in particular, there have been many attempts to
achieve more equitable prices for the producing countries. Rubber producers
want a more 'transparent' trading system, with prices set according to
worldwide demand and supply, and not through private party-to-party deals
between the plantations or smallholder groups and the main consumer
companies, mainly the tyre manufacturers.
Some moves towards such an open system at last seem likely. Consumer
companies have become concerned that, if prices remain low, there can be no
guarantee of long-term supply. Already several Malaysian rubber producers
have moved into more profitable palm oil - or sold their land for leisure
and real estate purposes.
The government faces an uphill battle in its attempt to achieve dynamic but
balanced overall economic development and to ensure the 3.5 per cent per
annum growth in the agricultural sector targeted in the present Sixth
Malaysia Plan. It seems inevitable that the more the manufacturing sector
prospers, the more constraints the agricultural sector will face. Wider
affluence has led to more food imports. Farmers continue to drift away from
the countryside. Malaysia's rice production fell by nearly 8 per cent last
year, and 20 per cent of local consumption has to be imported.
But the outlook is not wholly discouraging. In the first quarter of 1991,
overall agricultural production (including timber) increased by 7.7 per
cent. While rubber exports declined, palm oil showed a healthy increase. A
USDollars 500m government export credit financing programme for palm oil,
granting various countries deferred payment terms for the purchase of large
quantities of Malaysian production, has given new life to the palm oil
industry.
The emphasis now is on the development and expansion of agriculture-related
production facilities. Much has been invested in research and development,
and in downstream 'value added' activities. The palm oil sector is
diversifying more into the oil and fats market. The rubber sector is
producing more goods, including gloves and condoms.
The Sixth Malaysia Plan says that agriculture has reached a watershed. The
private sector, as in other industries, is expected to play a central role
in onward development:
'In contrast to the previous plans, when agricultural development was
largely public-sector driven, the emphasis will be on the important role of
the private sector in revitalising the agriculture sector,' it promises.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
