FT  28 AUG 92 / Letter: Over-shadowed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JOHN EAST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Observer (August 24) errs in stating that, in 1991, the Daily Mirror
regained the number one circulation spot among national newspapers. The Sun
overtook the Mirror in 1978 and has remained ahead ever since. The Sun has a
circulation of 3,567,863, some 700,000 more than the Mirror, according to
Audit Bureau of Circulation figures for February to July this year.
If Observer was referring to the combined sales figure of the Daily Mirror
and the Daily Record in Scotland, this should have been pointed out to your
readers.
John East,
circulation director,
News International
Newspapers,
PO Box 481,
Virginia Street,
London E1 9BD
