<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is always room on the schedules for a soap based in a hospital and
Nurses could provide another hit for Channel 4 and its policy of buying the
best of American soaps. The first of 22 episodes goes out at 10 pm and in
its favour is a script by the undisputed Queen of the genre, Susan Harris,
whose previous credits include the eponymous Soap and The Golden Girls. This
one is set in the casualty ward of a Miami hospital and its success depends
upon whether you get hooked on the well-differentiated, slightly oddball,
characters.
Tax concessions have covered much of northern Britain with conifer trees.
Survival Special (ITV, 8 pm) penetrates these new forests to track one of
the rarest of our indigenous birds, and the largest true hawk, the goshawk,
which in its protected environment successfully swoops down and eats other
animals. So rare is the goshawk that the producer keeps the site of the
filming secret.
Edinburgh Nights on BBC2 at 11.30 pm should boost the Fringe takings of
Louise Rennison whose show is a witty monologue about her 1960s' youth in
Leeds, New Zealand, and swinging London.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
