FT  28 AUG 92 / Technology (Worth Watching): Fingerprints on the plant pot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DNA fingerprinting is most commonly associated with forensic investigations
and paternity suits, but researchers at the CSIRO division of horticulture
in South Australia are using it to identify plants.
Their work may lead to the establishment of a commercial facility for
growers who want to guarantee the identity of their products and protect
their rights to plant varieties.
If, for example, a winery has produced a successful wine from a new grape
variety, it can be positively identified using DNA fingerprinting.
CSIRO has isolated small pieces of DNA, called microsatellites, which are
characteristic of grapevines but which show minor differences in length
between different varieties. CSIRO: Australia, 08 274 9244.
