<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Conference agrees basis for Bosnian peace deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TENTATIVE first step towards a long-term solution of the Yugoslav conflict
came yesterday, when the London peace conference ended with agreement by all
combatants on a framework for a negotiated settlement.
But there was still deep scepticism about whether the bitter war waged by
Bosnia's Serbs against the Moslem community would allow the survival of an
independent Bosnian state.
The conference, sponsored by the United Nations and the European Community,
agreed on an end to violence and sieges of towns, recognition of current
borders, speedier delivery of humanitarian aid, and closing of detention
camps. There is to be tighter enforcement of existing sanctions against
Serbia.
It was also confirmed that Lord Owen - once Labour foreign secretary and
former leader of the Social Democrats - would head the EC's Yugoslavia peace
effort. He will succeed Lord Carrington, who gave up the role on the eve of
the conference.
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general, said a lengthy period of
negotiations lay ahead. They will start in Geneva on September 3, when six
committees will start work on the future constitutional status of Bosnia,
the role of ethnic minorities in the republics of the former Yugoslavia, and
other issues.
Mr John Major, the prime minister and co-chairman of the conference,
insisted that while there would be 'setbacks', the two days of negotiations
had brought closer a peaceful solution of the conflict.
But he warned that pressure would continue to be brought to bear on all the
warring factions, including tougher sanctions, to press the case for peace.
'We cannot rely on the goodwill of the parties,' he said.
Mr Lawrence Eagleburger, the acting US secretary of state, attempted to
reassure Bosnia's Moslems after he delivered a tough message to Bosnia's
Serbs, led by Mr Radovan Karadzic.
'We will never accept any of the (territorial) gains by Bosnia's Serbs,' Mr
Eagleburger said.
Earlier in the day, Mr Karadzic had said he was prepared to give back 20 per
cent of the land seized by his forces.
By threatening tougher sanctions against Serbia, the conference appeared to
have made progress despite the fighting in Bosnia. In the latest outbreak,
nine people were reported killed when a mortar shell exploded into a queue
in a residential part of Sarajevo, the capital.
Pressure against the Serbs will be maintained when the nine-nation Western
European Union meets in London today. It is expected to impose a naval
blockade of Serbia.
The agreement reached at the London conference includes:
The cessation of violence in Bosnia. This includes the early lifting of
sieges of towns and cities; international supervision of heavy weapons; a
ban on all military flights and identification of all headquarters and
commanders of all armed units, including paramilitaries in the republic.
The conference has already asked Mr Boutros Ghali to recommend that the
security council posts observers on the Bosnia-Serbian borders and deploys
observers in Bosnia to monitor the withdrawal of all heavy weapons.
Humanitarian aid. Delivery of aid is to be speeded up by using more
international monitors. In addition, refugees should be 'progressively
returned' to their homes.
Detention camps. All detention camps are to be dismantled and closed
immediately. Aid organisations will look at ways of providing temporary
accommodation for those released but whose homes have been destroyed.
Sanctions. Trade sanctions against Serbia are to be more tightly enforced by
monitoring traffic on the river Danube and sending international experts to
Serbia's neighbours. The security council will be asked to prevent illegal
transfers of financial assets to Serbia and Montenegro and eliminate
diversion of goods in transit.
First light in bitter imbroglio, Page 2
