<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Individuals' shareholdings fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is further than ever from achieving its goal of creating a
nation of individual shareholders, according to figures released yesterday
by the Central Statistics Office.
In its August Economics Trends Bulletin, the CSO says the percentage of UK
quoted company shares held by individuals and unincorporated businesses fell
for the third successive year to just 20 per cent in January. The figure was
20.5 per cent in January 1991 and, in 1981, before most of the privatisation
programme had got under way, 37.5 per cent.
More than half UK company shares are in the hands of financial institutions.
Pension funds hold 31.1 per cent of the total, down marginally from 31.4 per
cent the year before, while insurance companies increased their percentage
by 0.3 per cent to 20.7 per cent.
The CSO noted that the latest drop in individual holdings comes despite the
privatisation of the electricity industry. Privatisation has been advocated
as a means of promoting wider share ownership.
However, the percentage held by individuals and unincorporated businesses of
the shares of the 10 largest privatised companies increased over the past
year to 22 per cent of outstanding shares, largely reflecting the sale of
the second tranche of the government's British Telecom stake.
Without the effects of that sale, however, individuals' holdings in
privatised companies fell to 17 per cent of the total from 17.9 per cent.
The CSO noted that its data was hampered by the existence of nominee
accounts, which obscure the ownership of a large portion of shares.
Holdings by the overseas sector rose by 1 percentage point to 12.8 per cent,
about level with the 1989 figure. In 1981 overseas shareholders owned just
3.6 per cent of the shares in UK companies.
Overseas shareholders now have 10 per cent of shares in privatised
companies. Thirty seven per cent of the overseas owners have holdings valued
at Pounds 100m or more.
The number of UK companies with ordinary shares listed on the London Stock
Exchange fell from 1,946 in December 31, 1990 to 1,852 in January this year.
Market capitalisation rose to Pounds 530.2bn from Pounds 445bn, primarily
because of higher share prices.
The UK spent Pounds 12.1bn on research and development in 1990 - 2.2 per
cent of gross domestic product, the same as in 1989. This was an increase in
real terms of 12 per cent since 1985.
Economic Trends No. 466, August 1992, HMSO Pounds 11.50
</TEXT>
