<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Abuses threaten to undermine construction industry: How a
proposed review of contract managementmay help improve the sector's image
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION lawyers like to tell stories about builders who come to them
seeking loopholes in tender contracts even before they bid for a job.
The companies want to know whether the contract has been so poorly worded
they will be able to claim extra payments from customers once work is under
way. There have been many tales of contractors that bid for contracts at a
loss, only to make a profit from claims. Developers anxious to finish
projects often find it cheaper to agree claims rather than try to re-let the
work.
Just as big a problem - particularly in the recession - has been late
payment of bills by main contractors, which sub-contractors say has forced
many medium-sized and small companies into receivership.
It is against this background that the government last week proposed a
review of contract arrangements in the construction industry. The
independent review, to be financed jointly by the government and the
industry, will examine the excessive reliance of companies on claims and
other contract abuses which sour the sector's image.
The last time the government examined the award and management of
construction contracts was in 1962. Three decades later customers are still
complaining of a 'claims culture' among contractors and sub-contractors who,
they say, use more energy protecting their individual financial and legal
positions than working together.
The Department of the Environment, which proposed the latest review, says
there is profound dissatisfaction with the adversarial nature of contractual
relationships on building sites.
Olympia &amp; York, when building the failed Canary Wharf in London's Docklands,
estimated the cost of construction in the UK was twice that in the US. Mr
Richard Griffiths, a senior vice-president at O&amp;Y, blamed this on a
confrontational approach adopted by the large numbers of separate,
independently controlled contractors that work on large developments. 'If
something goes wrong, the first thing you get is a claim rather than an
attempt to find a common solution to the problem,' he said.
The fragmented nature of construction work involving a range of specialist
skills means the industry will always be prone to contract disagreements.
The biggest area for claims is design changes, or variation orders, as they
are sometimes called. Anybody involved in domestic building work who has
asked for a radiator to be moved or a doorway enlarged once plans have been
completed will recognise the response: 'It can be done . . . but it will
cost you.'
Contractors building the Channel tunnel have claimed more than Pounds 1bn in
additional payments for fitting out rail tunnels and building passenger
terminals at Folkestone in Kent and Sangatte in northern France. Much of the
claim is to meet changes in design specifications which contractors say have
been made to satisfy improved safety requirements.
The review will also consider complaints that main contractors seek to boost
their cashflow by delaying payment of bills to sub-contractors who do most
of the actual work.
In a move to encourage faster payment to sub-contractors, ministers said
earlier this year that companies winning government construction contracts
would be expected to pay sub-contractors within 30 days of receiving a valid
invoice. Sub-contractors say the move so far has received a lukewarm
response from main contractors.
The British Constructional Steelwork Association says more than 100 members
and their subsidiaries have ceased trading since 1989 - some pushed over the
brink because main contractors have delayed payments.
The association says slow payments have been caused by delays in certifying
that work has been completed correctly. Main contractors may also query
bills knowing that sub-contractors will accept a lower payment rather than
risk long delays and potentially high legal costs pursuing additional money.
Serious problems have also arisen over retention money, held back by
developers and main contractors under the terms of a contract as insurance
against defects emerging after a job has been completed.
This money, normally between 3 per cent and 5 per cent of the total contract
value, can mean the difference between breaking even and making a loss in
the current depressed market.
This money should be repaid within 12 months of work finishing but disputes
can arise over what constitutes legal completion. Is it, for example, after
the last tree has been planted during landscaping? According to the
association one structural steel company waited five years after it
completed a project for retention money to be released.
Retention money technically belongs to the sub-contractor, but it can be
lost altogether if a developer or main contractor ceases trading. A number
of contractors that worked on Canary Wharf are threatened in this way,
including Graham Wood, the structural steel company which recently went into
receivership.
Practices like these, which have always gone on in the construction
industry, tend to get worse in recession. Construction lawyers can expect a
lot more work yet.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
