FT  28 AUG 92 / Acorn seeks move to wider market
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ACORN, the Cambridge-based personal-computer manufacturer which dominates
the UK schools market, is seeking to break out of its educational niche with
products aimed at the home and professionals.
Acorn, in which Olivetti of Italy has a majority stake, has had some
difficult years because of the recession and changes in schools' purchasing
policies. It hopes customers will be attracted by its ARM microprocessor, a
version of which is to be used by Apple Computer of the US in a pocket
computer called Newton.
Acorn's product list includes a home computer for Pounds 499, a 'home
office' system for Pounds 999 plus VAT, and a Pounds 250 electronic notebook
which is the first result of Acorn's collaboration with Psion, the UK
portable-computer manufacturer.
Last year Acorn recovered from a poor first half to record pre-tax profits
of Pounds 274,000, against Pounds 1.58m the year before.
