FT  28 AUG 92 / Man cleared of conspiracy charge
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A BUSINESSMAN alleged to have rifled the bank account of a firm of London
solicitors was yesterday cleared at Southwark Crown Court of conspiracy to
defraud.
It had been alleged that, with the help of an unknown accomplice, Mr Sean
O'Reilly, of Purley, Surrey, almost got away with more than Pounds 322,000
belonging to the solicitors, Asshetons, before the alleged fraud was
discovered.
The prosecution alleged that someone posing as a partner in Asshetons
instructed its bank to transfer money from its client account to one of Mr
O'Reilly's personal accounts.
The jury returned a unanimous not guilty verdict on the conspiracy charge.
Judge Geoffrey Rivlin QC ordered formal not guilty verdicts to be recorded
on charges of handling stolen goods and using a false instrument, both of
which Mr O'Reilly denied.
