<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Scientists enter race to find gravitational waves: British
Association for the Advancement of Science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNIE LYNCH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCIENTISTS around the world are competing to be first to measure nature's
most elusive radiation - gravitational waves - and so validate some of
Einstein's last predictions.
The competition has already brought some industrial spin-offs. A new
physical principle called 'squeezing light' has been discovered by Glasgow
researchers and is now used to reduce background noise in communication
systems.
Gravitational waves are ripples in the gravitational field around stars.
They travel at the speed of light. Since gravity is a weak force the tiny
disturbances caused by the ripples are hard to detect.
Indirect experimental evidence indicates that gravitational waves do exist,
as Einstein predicted in 1916. Direct experimental evidence is more
difficult to acquire.
Two forms of detector are being developed to measure gravitational waves.
Bar detectors - 2 metre cylinders of pure aluminium cooled to almost
absolute zero - oscillate naturally along their length. This effect should
be enhanced when the cylinders are hit by gravitational waves.
Professor David Schutz, of Cardiff University's physics department, said:
'The coldest object in the universe is sitting in a physics lab in Rome. All
physicists need now is an event with sufficient energy, such as a supernova
 -the calamitous death of a large star - to produce the waves.'
The second approach, in a joint British-German project, is the development
of giant interferometer detectors which do not need supernovae to produce
results. Interferometry is the measurement of small changes in length using
very pure light.
The detector's design involves simultaneously bouncing laser light off two
pairs of perfect mirrors, suspended at right angles to one another, and
looking for differences in the time taken for the light to reflect back.
If a gravitational wave hits, the mirrors will move slightly apart and the
return time will change. The distance between the mirrors is 3km to 4km and
the mirror movement is a million million millionth of a metre.
The whole interferometer is kept in a vacuum to isolate it from background
noise.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
</DOC>
