</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL, PITTSBURGH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MAPLE LEAF FOODS, Canada's biggest food processor which is controlled by
Hillsdown of the UK, said second-quarter profits from continuing operations
were up 29 per cent to CDollars 20m (USDollars 17m) or 25 cents a share.
This compares with CDollars 15.6m,or 24 cents a share, last year.
Sales fell to CDollars 678m, against CDollars 808m last time, due mainly to
the sale of its edible oils business.
First-half earnings from continuing operations were CDollars 32m, or 40
cents a share, up from CDollars 24.7m, or 38 cents a share, a year earlier
on fewer shares outstanding. Sales were CDollars 1.3bn, against CDollars
1.55bn.
Maple Leaf, with operations across Canada and in the US and Europe, said
results for the second half would probably be affected by the weak economic
recovery and poor weather.
HJ Heinz, the US food group, and Hillsdown of the UK have formed a joint
venture to acquire a Hungarian state-owned canning company, Kecskemeti
Konzervgyar of Kecskemet, Reuter reports from Pittsburg.
The venture will be known as Magyar Foods.
