<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / International Company News: Decline at BASF deepens gloom in
chemical sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BASF's first-half figures yesterday showed that the trials of the German
chemical industry were continuing and likely to keep profits in the sector
under pressure for some time.
The result was the worst of the three big German chemical concerns. Hoechst
on Wednesday announced a poor performance while Bayer reported better than
expected, though still lower, figures.
BASF's interim pre-tax profits were 37 per cent lower at DM972m (Dollars
607m), with net income down by 33 per cent at DM465m.
Hoechst reported a 20 per cent drop in first-half pre-tax profits and Bayer
one of 10 per cent. Both said they saw little evidence of any improvement on
world markets. BASF yesterday echoed this comment. Noting that 1992 remained
a difficult year, it added: 'As yet, there are no reliable signs of any
improvement, especially in the US.'
It said rising labour costs, higher environmental protection costs, and the
slackening of business in the holiday period meant the second half was
unlikely to bring any marked improvement in earnings. Commenting on the poor
first-half figures, it said demand had not weakened but excess capacity in
the industry and low prices hampered performance.
BASF's group turnover was 0.6 per cent higher at DM23.6bn, but the company,
which has a large energy subsidiary, said the downward trend was concealed
by the increase in the mineral oil tax which added about DM500m.
BASF had to accept sharp price reductions over a wide range of products. The
lower dollar had added to this pressure, without providing adequate relief
on the raw materials side. In spite of lacklustre economic growth, volume
sales increased in all markets, partly due to new plants.
In the US, 'our business reflects the fact that the expected upturn has yet
to materialise,' the company said. The group is continuing with its
cost-cutting and labour reduction programmes, with the labour force down by
3 per cent to less than 127,000 people in the first six months.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
