<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Exports rise for small companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUST OVER half of Britain's smaller exporters increased overseas sales in
the 12 months to July, while a further 18 per cent maintained volumes.
This is one of the main findings of a quarterly survey of smaller exporters
published yesterday by the Small Business Research Trust for the Royal Bank
of Scotland.
Most exporters managed to maintain profit margins on export sales in spite
of increased competition and the government's commitment to keeping the
pound within its fluctuation range in the European exchange rate mechanism.
In recent months exporters have become slightly more optimistic about
overseas markets, the survey noted. There was some evidence that many small
companies had successfully switched from the UK market to export markets
with the expectation of improving their performance.
Small businesses employing 15 or more people were more successful in
increasing exports than companies employing fewer than 15.
The Netherlands, Spain, Portugal and the Middle East were regarded as the
most favourable overseas markets but prospects in North America had
deteriorated.
The main competition for smaller British exporters came not from other UK
exporters nor from local businesses in the export markets but from larger
companies in third countries. Many new companies, particularly those based
in Asia, had entered export markets.
One of the biggest problems facing smaller exporters was the widespread
copying by larger companies of products and techniques pioneered by small
companies.
The most common response to increased competition was for the British
exporter to cut prices (58 per cent) followed by improving the product or
service (53 per cent), switching to a new market (48 per cent) and
introducing new products or services (40 per cent).
The Royal Bank of Scotland Quarterly Survey of Exporters. Marketing
Department, Royal Bank of Scotland, Birchin Court, 20 Birchin Lane, London
EC3V 9DJ. Free.
</TEXT>
