<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Poll tax hits vote registration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE that the poll tax caused fewer people to register as voters is
shown in a survey published yesterday.
The survey, by the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys for the Home
Office, found that the percentage of households returning a form for the
1991 electoral register was lower than in any of the previous annual
surveys. The forms would have been sent out in early autumn 1990, shortly
after the introduction of the poll tax.
Just over half the councils in England and Wales received a completed form
from at least 95 per cent of households. The response rate for a quarter of
the councils was less than 90 per cent, and less than 80 per cent for one in
11.
These figures reverse the improvement in response rates recorded since the
survey began in 1987. The biggest fall was recorded in London - where
poll-tax rates were among the highest - with the average response rate at 89
per cent, 3 per cent down from 1990.
About half of local authorities now leave the names of voters who registered
in earlier years on the register for up to three years, even if no
registration form is returned. More than half the authorities used the
poll-tax register to add names to the electoral register.
More than 90 per cent of councils believe their poll-tax backlogs will not
have a significant impact on their implementing the council tax, according
to a report by consultants CSL services for the Department of the
Environment.
Compiling the electoral register 1991. HMSO. Pounds 8.
</TEXT>
