FT  28 AUG 92 / Patten moves on school surplus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL education authorities in England have been given three months to
produce detailed plans for reducing surplus school places.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, said yesterday that he aims to take
statutory powers to impose plans if authorities do not produce satisfactory
proposals to eliminate the estimated 1.5m surplus places.
He also intends to take powers to close grant-maintained schools which have
an unacceptable number of surplus places. This raises for the first time the
prospect of the forced closure of schools that have opted out of local
education authority control.
Since opting-out has proved attractive to schools threatened with closure by
their local authority, the consequences could be far-reaching for the
government's policy of encouraging all schools to seek grant-maintained
status.
Mr Patten made an exception for 'scattered communities and small schools,
particularly those in rural areas, which face special problems'. Such
schools are mainly in rural Tory constituencies, and backbench Tory MPs will
be resistant to plans to close their village schools wholesale.
