<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Ombudsman warns on pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S pensions ombudsman said yesterday he was able to resolve
only 47 of more than 2,100 complaints received by his office last year.
Nearly half were rejected for consideration because they were either out of
his jurisdiction or concerned events that happened too long ago.
Mr Michael Platt was delivering the first annual report since the office was
established early in 1991.
'I think it only right to record that my inability to act in these
circumstances has given rise to a sense of frustration among the members of
some schemes who are worried that their pension rights may be insecure,' he
said.
He added that this lack of power should be taken up by government advisers
currently reviewing pensions law.
Some of the complaints received by his office but determined to be out of
his jurisdiction concerned employers' use of pension scheme surpluses for
their own purposes. Mr Platt urged the government to consider clarifying in
law the question of the ownership of surpluses.
The average complaint took seven months to handle, which Mr Platt said was
too long to meet the requirements of the Citizen's Charter. Delays had
occurred partly through the difficulties involved in setting up the
ombudsman's office. Additional staff had recently been hired.
Of the 47 complaints resolved by his office, only 18 were upheld in favour
of the complainant and a further four decisions supported the complainant in
part. In most of the other cases, the complaint was not upheld.
A spokesman for the National Association of Pension Funds, the industry's
trade organisation, said the fact that fewer than half the complaints proved
justified was evidence that serious problems did not exist in the industry.
'The number of complaints upheld is quite reassuringly low,' he said. The
current trust law governing pension arrangements was probably adequate, he
said.
</TEXT>
