<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / International Company News: Fairfax exceeds prospectus
forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JOHN Fairfax Holdings, the Australian newspaper group controlled by Mr
Conrad Black, yesterday unveiled pre-tax profits for the year to June which
exceeded forecasts in its pre-flotation prospectus.
Profits before interest and tax increased by 9.8 per cent to ADollars 129.8m
(USDollars 93.3m), on turnover up 2.8 per cent to ADollars 729.1m. The group
said in March that pre-tax profits would increase to ADollars 123m on
turnover of ADollars 723m.
Fairfax also said it was entitled to ADollars 650m in tax credits, up from
ADollars 323m in the prospectus, which suggests the group is unlikely to pay
income tax for at least five years. Sir Zelman Cowen, chairman, said the
result was 'extremely good' in the light of 'a very difficult economic
environment' caused by Australia's slow recovery from recession. Earnings
since June had been 'broadly in line with projections, despite the
continuing recession and uneven trends in advertising volumes.'
Analysts said profitability had increased markedly since January, when
Fairfax was acquired for ADollars 1.4bn by the Tourang consortium led by Mr
Black's UK Daily Telegraph.
The group said second-half earnings before tax and interest were 11 per cent
higher at ADollars 60.1m, on revenue of ADollars 357.4m, up 1.6 per cent on
the prospectus forecast. Operating costs fell 0.4 per cent to ADollars
285.8m.
Net profit was 29 per cent higher than expected at ADollars 15.5m, after net
interest expenses of ADollars 33.1m and income tax of ADollars 11.5m.
However, the group said the tax bill would be offset against the tax
credits. It did not declare a dividend, in line with its prospectus
forecasts.
Fairfax said circulation of all its main titles increased, but advertising
volumes fell sharply. However, advertising revenue was unchanged at ADollars
534m, indicating a significant improvement in margins.
More than 160 staff had left through early retirements and voluntary
redundancies suggesting that costs are likely to fall further.
Following a flotation in May, the Telegraph owns 15 per cent of Fairfax.
Hellman and Friedman, the US investment bank, owns 5 per cent in the form of
non-voting debentures, and Australian financial institutions own the rest.
