<HEADLINE>
FT  28 AUG 92 / Money Markets: Cautious trading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A CAUTIOUS calm returned to both the sterling cash and futures markets
yesterday as the pound continued to hold above its floor in the European
exchange rate mechanism.
The Bank of England's large intervention to support sterling appeared to
have been initially successful, although dealers feel that the pound will
next come under renewed pressure in the run-up to the French referendum on
the Maastricht treaty.
A late fall in the pound against the D-Mark also triggered new depression in
futures.
In the morning, short sterling futures rose sharply as confidence about the
currency spread, although they continue to price in a base rate rise of at
least  1/2 percentage point.
In late trading they fell back, as the pound took new losses on the foreign
exchanges. The September short sterling contract closed 1 basis point up
from its previous finish, at 89.18. The December contract closed up 1 basis
point to finish at 89.18. Volumes traded were again high, at more than
45,000 lots.
Period rates in the sterling cash market softened. Three-month money was
down by a  1/4 of a per cent on the offered side to 10 5/8 per cent, while
the 1-year rate was down to 10 13/16 per cent from a previous close of 11
per cent. One-month money was back on what dealers called 'the right side of
10 base rate': it closed at 10 1/4 per cent on the offered side from a
previous close of 10 9/16 per cent.
The Bank of England's operations in the sterling money market reflected the
easier tone. For the first three days of this week, dealers had rushed to
offer paper to the Bank, fearing an imminent rise in base rates. Yesterday,
the market took the whole day to remove the shortage of Pounds 1.1bn.
In the morning, the Bank bought Pounds 20m of Band 3 Treasury bills at 9 3/4
per cent, Pounds 60m of Band 3 bank bills, Pounds 82m of Band 4 bank bills
at 9 per cent, and Pounds 30m in a repurchase agreement at 9 15/16 per cent.
The forecast was later revised to Pounds 1bn and the Bank purchased Pounds
1m of Band 4 bank bills. In the afternoon, it purchased Pounds 62m of Band 1
Treasury bills at 9 7/8 per cent, Pounds 139m of Band 1 bank bills, Pounds
48m of Band 3 bank bills and Pounds 2m in Band 4 bank bills.
There was Pounds 405m of late assistance.
</TEXT>
